<!--
Part E – Sticky Position 
17.Create a navigation bar using position: sticky. 
18.Make the navbar stick to the top of the page when scrolling. 
19.Add multiple content sections to test the sticky behavior. 
20.Explain the difference between fixed and sticky.
-->

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Sticky Position</title>

    <style>
        body {
            margin: 0;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }

        /* Header */
        .header {
            background-color: lightgray;
            padding: 20px;
            text-align: center;
        }

        /* Sticky Navbar */
        .navbar {
            position: sticky;
            top: 0;
            background-color: steelblue;
            padding: 15px;
        }

        .navbar a {
            color: white;
            text-decoration: none;
            margin-right: 20px;
        }

        /* Content Sections */
        .section {
            height: 500px;
            padding: 20px;
            border-bottom: 1px solid black;
        }

        .section:nth-child(even) {
            background-color: #f2f2f2;
        }

        .section:nth-child(odd) {
            background-color: #dddddd;
        }
    </style>
</head>

<body>

    <div class="header">
        <h1>Sticky Navigation Bar Example</h1>
        <p>Scroll down to see the sticky effect.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="navbar">
        <a href="#section1">Section 1</a>
        <a href="#section2">Section 2</a>
        <a href="#section3">Section 3</a>
        <a href="#section4">Section 4</a>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="section1">
        <h2>Section 1</h2>
        <p>This is the first content section.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="section2">
        <h2>Section 2</h2>
        <p>This is the second content section.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="section3">
        <h2>Section 3</h2>
        <p>This is the third content section.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="section" id="section4">
        <h2>Section 4</h2>
        <p>This is the fourth content section.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Observation and Explanation</h2>

    <p>
        The navigation bar uses <code>position: sticky</code> with
        <code>top: 0</code>. When the page is scrolled and the navbar reaches
        the top of the viewport, it sticks there and remains visible.
    </p>

    <p>
        Multiple content sections are added to make the page scrollable and to
        demonstrate the sticky behavior.
    </p>

    <h2>Difference Between Fixed and Sticky</h2>

    <p>
        <strong>Fixed Position:</strong> The element is always positioned
        relative to the browser viewport and remains visible even while
        scrolling.
    </p>

    <p>
        <strong>Sticky Position:</strong> The element behaves like a normal
        element until it reaches a specified scroll position. It then sticks
        to that position while scrolling within its container.
    </p>

</body>
</html>
